claim.content:
Extrapolating the Fermi liquid parameters divided by effective mass to the thermodynamic limit using the procedure above yields the following representative numerical estimates with quoted uncertainties inherited from the ordinary least-squares extrapolations.  For the paramagnetic (unpolarized) 2D HEG the extrapolated values of $F_{l}^{s,a}/m^{*}$ are approximately:
      at $r_{s}=1$: $F_{0}^{s}/m^{*}=-0.2(2)$, $F_{1}^{s}/m^{*}=-0.18(3)$ (antisymmetric components given similarly in the full data);
      at $r_{s}=5$: $F_{0}^{s}/m^{*}=0.7(8)$, $F_{1}^{s}/m^{*}=-0.03(2)$;
      at $r_{s}=10$: $F_{0}^{s}/m^{*}=-1(1)$, $F_{1}^{s}/m^{*}=-0.1(3)$.  For the fully ferromagnetic 2D HEG the extrapolated values of $F_{l}/m^{*}$ are approximately:
      at $r_{s}=1$: $F_{0}/m^{*}=-0.50(4)$, $F_{1}/m^{*}=-0.22(3)$;
      at $r_{s}=5$: $F_{0}/m^{*}=-1.5(2)$, $F_{1}/m^{*}=-0.61(6)$;
      at $r_{s}=10$: $F_{0}/m^{*}=-1.8(3)$, $F_{1}/m^{*}=-1.03(3)$.  These extrapolated numbers carry large uncertainties arising from oscillatory finite-size (shell-filling) behavior that dominates the nominal statistical error bars from individual DMC runs.

